# Immediate execution order

## Sprint 1

* map all publish listing code paths
* define canonical listing schema
* define listing state machine
* identify payment and expiration bugs

## Sprint 2

* add audit scripts and regression tests
* fix publish / payment / expiration issues
* validate public listing correctness end to end

## Sprint 3

* formalize dealer / fleet dealer / admin roles
* add profile and permissions model
* add dealer-scoped listing ownership rules

## Sprint 4

* build Meta Business connection flow
* store and validate connected assets
* add dealer settings for Meta publishing

## Sprint 5

* generate Meta feed from clean published listings
* add sync logs and basic error handling

---

# Success criteria

## Listing audit is complete when:

* no paid listing can fail silently
* no unpaid listing can publish incorrectly
* expiration dates are deterministic
* public listing data matches stored listing data
* image and listing references are consistent
* regression tests cover the core flow

## Dealer Meta connection is complete when:

* dealer admin can connect Meta Business assets
* TimberEquip stores assets at dealer scope
* permissions are validated
* connected assets can be used for future catalog sync

---

# Final guidance

Do not treat these as two equal projects.

The listing audit comes first.
If listing state, payment state, and expiration state are unreliable, every Meta integration built on top of it will be brittle and expensive to debug.
